fields.title: NAVI BEAT FAZE TO WIN PGL MAJOR COPENHAGEN_
fields.content:
Natus Vincere have won PGL Major Copenhagen after defeating FaZe in a highly-entertaining series that peaked at over 1.8 million concurrent viewers - the third-highest in Counter-Strike history - and snapped a streak of seven Major finals decided in just two maps._

For a while, it seemed that victory would elude NAVI. They came out of the gate swinging and stole FaZe's map pick, only to get immediately destroyed on their own pick. But where most teams would have collapsed, NAVI responded with a masterclass performance on Inferno, where Valeriy "⁠b1t⁠" Vakhovskiy and Justinas "⁠jL⁠" Lekavicius combined for 43 frags in a 13-3 rout. The Lithuanian player capped off a fantastic tournament run with a 1.23 rating in the final to earn his first MVP medal.


    The victory serves as vindication for several NAVI players, especially Aleksi "⁠Aleksib⁠" Virolainen, who finally claimed a Major crown after a rough few years following his departure from ENCE.

"It feels unreal," Aleksib said after the match. "None of this would have been possible without the teammates I have. So selfless, everybody doing tons of work. For the past six months, we've had ups and downs. Everybody worked their ass off. B1ad3 deserves respect as well. He made me a better IGL and he's the best coach in the world."

With this win, NAVI become only the third organization to win more than one Major, joining fnatic and Astralis in this exclusive club. And b1t adds a second Major trophy to his résumé, joining Peter "⁠dupreeh⁠" Rasmussen, Dan "⁠apEX⁠" Madesclaire and Emil "⁠Magisk⁠" Reif as the only players to have won Majors speaking two different languages.

The veto featured a surprise Ancient pick from FaZe, who had played the map only twice at this Major, with mixed results (10-13 loss to HEROIC and a 13-7 victory over FURIA). Starting on the offense, FaZe carved out an early lead, but Natus Vincere quickly took control of proceedings, powered by a stunning hat-trick of jL frags that included a one-tap.

Natus Vincere frustrated FaZe with a textbook defensive display, keeping Finn "⁠karrigan⁠" Andersen's men at bay for the majority of the half. Still, FaZe were able to find the occasional round and managed to head to half-time chasing only a two-round deficit.

Natus Vincere added to their lead after winning the ensuing pistol round in style, and they rode that momentum to a 10-5 lead. With guns in hand, FaZe enjoyed a spell in the ascendency and closed the gap to just one round. It seemed like a classic FaZe comeback was in the making, but Natus Vincere kept their composure. jL stopped that streak with a successful 1v1 and then, just when FaZe were about to win a round where they had just one SMG to work with, he pulled off a sensational 1v3 clutch to put the game to bed.

FaZe started Mirage off on the wrong foot as they wasted a 4vs2 advantage in the pistol round, but they recovered immediately on a force buy and ran away with the game. Natus Vincere could only win one more round in the entire half, and their comeback hopes were quashed after the side switch as Robin "⁠ropz⁠" Kool clutched a 1v2 situation, powering FaZe to a statement victory.

The shock of the Mirage blowout was soon forgotten as NAVI came out on Inferno looking refreshed. By the sixth round, karrigan had already used up two of his three timeouts as his team struggled to break through a stubborn NAVI defense led by b1t. It took a massive 1v3 clutch by David "⁠frozen⁠" Čerňanský on 5 HP for FaZe to get on the board, but they would only pick up two more rounds in the half as NAVI's players kept their cool.

More misery was to come for FaZe as NAVI hit double digits after a fast A push in the pistol round. With their economy in shambles, karrigan's troops were helpless to prevent their opponents from taking the map and the series.

I will probably give an unpopular opinion about the possible transfer of m0NESY to Cloud9.

I think this is not the career option that will suit m0nesy.
I think that in C9 he will not be able to produce consistently strong performances; he wont be able to reach his full potential in Cloud9.

I will assume that C9 as a team, in terms of atmosphere, and in general, is very different from G2.
In G2, m0NESY has quite freedom and players treat him like a younger brother (I exaggerate, but I think you can say that), in C9 it wont be the same.
And if C9 does not have the desired / expected results further, Ilya will be devoured.

I think good option for hiim would be stay in G2 and wait for upgrades in the current roster. I doubt that G2 wont make changes this season.
